window.CISSP_DOMAIN_CONTENT[1] = {"title": "Domain 1: Security and Risk Management", "html": "\n<h4>1. The CIA Triad & DAD Triad</h4>\n<p>The foundation of information security rests on the <strong>CIA Triad</strong>: Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability. Every control, policy, and technology is designed to protect one or more of these principles. The opposite of the CIA Triad is the <strong>DAD Triad</strong>: Disclosure, Alteration, and Destruction.</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Confidentiality:</strong> Preventing unauthorized disclosure of information. <em>Threats:</em> Shoulder surfing, social engineering, packet sniffing. <em>Controls:</em> Encryption, access controls, classification.</li>\n  <li><strong>Integrity:</strong> Ensuring information is accurate and unaltered. <em>Threats:</em> Unauthorized modifications, bit rot. <em>Controls:</em> Hashing, digital signatures, configuration management.</li>\n  <li><strong>Availability:</strong> Ensuring authorized users have timely access. <em>Threats:</em> DoS/DDoS attacks, hardware failure, power outages. <em>Controls:</em> Redundancy (RAID, clustering), backups, UPS.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>2. Identification, Authentication, Authorization, & Accountability (IAAA)</h4>\n<p>The core lifecycle of access control is governed by the <strong>IAAA Model</strong>. It must be implemented in order:</p>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Identification:</strong> Claiming an identity (e.g., username, scanning a badge). Not secure on its own.</li>\n  <li><strong>Authentication:</strong> Proving the claimed identity (e.g., password, biometrics, hardware token).</li>\n  <li><strong>Authorization:</strong> Granting rights and permissions based on the authenticated identity (e.g., read/write access to files).</li>\n  <li><strong>Accountability:</strong> Tracking user actions and mapping them back to a unique identity. Requires auditing, logs, and non-repudiation.</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"tip-box\" style=\"background: rgba(14,165,233,0.08); border-left: 4px solid var(--accent); padding: 15px; border-radius: 4px; margin-top: 16px;\">\n  <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> Identification must happen first. Without unique identification, you cannot establish accountability. Group accounts (like 'Admin' or 'Guest') destroy accountability because you cannot prove who performed an action.\n</div>\n\n<h4>3. Security Governance & Policy Hierarchy</h4>\n<p>Governance is the system by which an organization is directed and controlled. It starts at the top (Board of Directors and C-level executive team) and trickles down via the policy hierarchy:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Policies:</strong> High-level documents signed by senior management. They define the security posture and direction. Mandatory.</li>\n  <li><strong>Standards:</strong> Specific, mandatory requirements or rules (e.g., \"All passwords must be at least 14 characters\").</li>\n  <li><strong>Baselines:</strong> Minimum security levels or configurations (e.g., \"Windows Server 2022 baseline configuration\"). Mandatory.</li>\n  <li><strong>Guidelines:</strong> Flexible recommendations or best practices. Non-mandatory/advisory.</li>\n  <li><strong>Procedures:</strong> Step-by-step instructions on how to accomplish a task (e.g., \"How to reset a user's password\"). Mandatory.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Quantitative Risk Analysis & Equations</h4>\n<p>Quantitative risk analysis assigns dollar values to assets, threats, and risks. The math is highly tested on the CISSP exam:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Asset Value (AV):</strong> The monetary worth of an asset.</li>\n  <li><strong>Exposure Factor (EF):</strong> The percentage of asset loss suffered from a single realized threat (ranges from 0% to 100%).</li>\n  <li><strong>Single Loss Expectancy (SLE):</strong> The cost of a single occurrence of a threat.\n    <span class=\"formula-box\">SLE = AV \u00d7 EF</span>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO):</strong> How many times a year a threat is expected to occur (can be fractional, e.g., 0.1 for once in 10 years).</li>\n  <li><strong>Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE):</strong> The yearly cost of a risk.\n    <span class=\"formula-box\">ALE = SLE \u00d7 ARO</span>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"tip-box\" style=\"background: rgba(16,185,129,0.08); border-left: 4px solid var(--primary); padding: 15px; border-radius: 4px; margin-top: 16px;\">\n  <strong>Quantitative Example:</strong> A server is worth $100,000 (AV). A fire would cause 40% damage (EF). A fire is expected once every 5 years (ARO = 0.2).<br>\n  - SLE = $100,000 * 0.40 = $40,000<br>\n  - ALE = $40,000 * 0.2 = $8,000 per year.\n</div>\n\n<h4>5. Qualitative Risk Analysis</h4>\n<p>Qualitative risk analysis uses descriptive, subjective ratings (e.g., High, Medium, Low) rather than exact dollar values. It is based on opinion, experience, and scenarios:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Delphi Technique:</strong> An anonymous, iterative consensus-building method. Experts answer questionnaires in multiple rounds. Anonymity prevents groupthink and dominant personalities from taking over.</li>\n  <li><strong>Brainstorming:</strong> Group discussions to identify threats and risks.</li>\n  <li><strong>Risk Matrix:</strong> A grid that maps Probability vs. Impact to determine risk levels.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>6. Risk Responses</h4>\n<p>Once a risk is identified and analyzed, management must choose a risk response strategy:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Mitigation:</strong> Reducing risk by implementing controls (e.g., installing antivirus, firewalls, patching).</li>\n  <li><strong>Transfer (Sharing):</strong> Shifting the financial burden of risk to a third party (e.g., buying cyber insurance, outsourcing operations).</li>\n  <li><strong>Avoidance:</strong> Eliminating the risk entirely by stopping the activity (e.g., disabling a risky service, shutting down a business line).</li>\n  <li><strong>Acceptance:</strong> Agreeing to bear the risk because the cost of controls exceeds the potential loss. Requires executive sign-off.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>7. Security Controls & Types</h4>\n<p>Controls are countermeasures put in place to manage risk. They are categorized by <strong>How they are implemented</strong> and <strong>What they do</strong>:</p>\n<table style=\"width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; margin:12px 0;\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr style=\"background:rgba(255,255,255,0.05)\">\n      <th style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); text-align:left; font-size:12px;\">Category</th>\n      <th style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); text-align:left; font-size:12px;\">Technical (Logical)</th>\n      <th style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); text-align:left; font-size:12px;\">Administrative (Managerial)</th>\n      <th style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); text-align:left; font-size:12px;\">Physical (Operational)</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\"><strong>Preventive</strong></td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Firewall, Encryption, MFA</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Security awareness, Hiring check</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Fences, Mantraps, Locks</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr style=\"background:rgba(255,255,255,0.02)\">\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\"><strong>Detective</strong></td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">IDS, Logs audit, SIEM alerts</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Job rotation, Mandatory vacation</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">CCTV, Motion sensors, Guards</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\"><strong>Corrective</strong></td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Antivirus quarantine, Rebuild server</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Disciplinary actions, BCP trigger</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Fire suppression system trigger</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h4>8. Business Continuity (BC) vs. Disaster Recovery (DR)</h4>\n<p>Though closely linked, BCP and DRP serve different purposes. BCP focus is business process uptime; DRP focus is IT resource restoration.</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD):</strong> The maximum time a business process can be down before causing irreparable harm.</li>\n  <li><strong>Recovery Time Objective (RTO):</strong> The target time for restoring a system or service. Must be less than or equal to MTD.</li>\n  <li><strong>Recovery Point Objective (RPO):</strong> The maximum acceptable age of data that can be lost (defines backup frequency).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>9. Personnel Security Controls</h4>\n<p>People are often the weakest link in security. Organizations implement administrative controls to protect against insider threats:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Separation of Duties (SoD):</strong> Splitting a single sensitive task among multiple people to prevent fraud. Collusion is required to bypass this.</li>\n  <li><strong>Job Rotation:</strong> Periodically moving employees to different roles. Helps detect fraud and provides redundancy.</li>\n  <li><strong>Mandatory Vacation:</strong> Requiring employees to take consecutive days off. Allows others to audit their work, detecting unauthorized actions.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>10. Threat Modeling Frameworks</h4>\n<p>Threat modeling is a systematic process to identify, rate, and mitigate security threats:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>STRIDE (Developer Focus):</strong> Spoofing (Confidentiality), Tampering (Integrity), Repudiation (Non-repudiation), Information Disclosure (Confidentiality), Denial of Service (Availability), Elevation of Privilege (Authorization).</li>\n  <li><strong>PASTA:</strong> Process for Attack Simulation and Threat Analysis. Risk-centric, aligned with business objectives.</li>\n  <li><strong>DREAD:</strong> Damage, Reproducibility, Exploitability, Affected Users, Discoverability (scoring system).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>11. Intellectual Property (IP) & International Treaties</h4>\n<p>Legal protections for intellectual assets vary by type and duration:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Patents:</strong> Protect inventions (novel, useful, non-obvious). Duration: 20 years. Must be public.</li>\n  <li><strong>Copyrights:</strong> Protect original works of authorship (code, literature, music). Duration: Author's life plus 70 years (or 95 years for corporations).</li>\n  <li><strong>Trademarks:</strong> Protect brand names, logos, slogans. Can be renewed indefinitely.</li>\n  <li><strong>Trade Secrets:</strong> Proprietary business information (e.g., Coca-Cola formula). Protected as long as kept secret.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>12. Privacy Regulations & GDPR</h4>\n<p>Key global privacy frameworks protect personally identifiable information (PII):</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>GDPR (European Union):</strong> Strict rules on PII. Includes the <em>Right to Be Forgotten</em> (Right to Erasure) and a mandatory <em>72-hour breach notification</em> window.</li>\n  <li><strong>HIPAA (United States):</strong> Protects Protected Health Information (PHI). Enforces security and privacy rules for healthcare providers.</li>\n  <li><strong>CCPA (California):</strong> Gives residents rights over their personal data collected by businesses.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>13. Legal Concepts: Criminal, Civil, and Administrative Law</h4>\n<p>Security practitioners must operate within legal boundaries:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Criminal Law:</strong> Protects public peace and safety. Punishment: jail time, fines.</li>\n  <li><strong>Civil (Tort) Law:</strong> Resolves disputes between individuals/organizations. Punishment: financial damages.</li>\n  <li><strong>Administrative (Regulatory) Law:</strong> Regulations created by government agencies (e.g., FTC, SEC rules).</li>\n  <li><strong>Due Care:</strong> Doing what a reasonable person would do in a situation (acting responsibly).</li>\n  <li><strong>Due Diligence:</strong> The research and verification done to ensure due care is functioning (proving responsibility).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>14. ISC2 Code of Ethics</h4>\n<p>A CISSP candidate must strictly adhere to the ISC2 Code of Ethics. The four canons must be applied in exact order of priority:</p>\n<ol>\n  <li>Protect society, the common good, necessary public trust and confidence, and the infrastructure.</li>\n  <li>Act honorably, honestly, justly, responsibly, and legally.</li>\n  <li>Provide diligent and competent service to principals (employers/clients).</li>\n  <li>Advance and protect the profession.</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"tip-box\" style=\"background: rgba(239,68,68,0.08); border-left: 4px solid #ef4444; padding: 15px; border-radius: 4px; margin-top: 16px;\">\n  <strong>Exam Trap:</strong> If an employer orders you to perform an illegal action, Canon 1 and Canon 2 override Canon 3 (loyalty to employer). You must refuse the command or report it. Always prioritize public safety and law over corporate interest.\n</div>\n"};

window.CISSP_DOMAIN_CONTENT[2] = {"title": "Domain 2: Asset Security", "html": "\n<h4>1. The Data Classification Lifecycle</h4>\n<p>Data must be protected throughout its entire lifecycle. The stages are:</p>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Create (or Collect):</strong> Data is generated or acquired. This is the moment classification should be assigned.</li>\n  <li><strong>Classify:</strong> Assigning a classification label based on sensitivity and business impact.</li>\n  <li><strong>Store:</strong> Placing the data in a secure repository with appropriate access controls, encryption, and backups.</li>\n  <li><strong>Use:</strong> Accessing and processing the data. Data-in-use protections (e.g., memory enclave encryption) apply here.</li>\n  <li><strong>Archive:</strong> Moving inactive data to long-term, lower-cost storage. Must retain access controls and integrity checks.</li>\n  <li><strong>Destroy:</strong> Permanently sanitizing or physically destroying the media when data is no longer needed.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h4>2. Government vs. Commercial Classification Labels</h4>\n<p>Different environments use different labeling schemes to denote sensitivity levels:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Government / Military Labels:</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Top Secret:</em> Exceptionally grave damage to national security if disclosed.</li>\n      <li><em>Secret:</em> Serious damage to national security if disclosed.</li>\n      <li><em>Confidential:</em> Damage to national security if disclosed.</li>\n      <li><em>Unclassified:</em> Publicly releasable, but may still require protection (e.g., FOUO - For Official Use Only).</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Commercial / Private Sector Labels:</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Proprietary / Confidential:</em> Highly sensitive corporate data (e.g., trade secrets, source code, strategy).</li>\n      <li><em>Private:</em> Personal data of employees or customers (PII/PHI). Subject to regulations.</li>\n      <li><em>Sensitive:</em> Internal data that is not public but has lower sensitivity (e.g., company directory).</li>\n      <li><em>Public:</em> Low-sensitivity data intended for public consumption (e.g., marketing sheets, public website).</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>3. Asset Security Roles & Responsibilities</h4>\n<p>Understanding who owns and is responsible for data security is crucial for the exam:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Data Owner (Information Owner):</strong> A senior manager ultimately responsible for the data. They determine classification levels, define access requirements, and authorize access.</li>\n  <li><strong>Data Custodian:</strong> Hands-on IT staff (systems administrators) responsible for implementing the protections defined by the Owner. Tasks: backing up data, configuring ACLs, maintaining databases.</li>\n  <li><strong>Data Steward:</strong> Focuses on data quality, integrity, and metadata standards rather than security configuration.</li>\n  <li><strong>Data Processor:</strong> A third party that processes data on behalf of a Data Controller (the entity that owns the data). GDPR places direct compliance obligations on processors.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Privacy & Data States</h4>\n<p>Personally Identifiable Information (PII) and Protected Health Information (PHI) must be protected across three distinct states:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Data at Rest:</strong> Saved on persistent storage (HDDs, SSDs, backup tapes). <em>Protections:</em> Full disk encryption (FDE), folder/file-level encryption, physical storage locks.</li>\n  <li><strong>Data in Transit (Motion):</strong> Moving over a network. <em>Protections:</em> Transport Layer Security (TLS), IPsec VPNs, HTTPS, SSH.</li>\n  <li><strong>Data in Use:</strong> Loaded into RAM or CPU registers during processing. <em>Protections:</em> Confidential computing, hardware memory encryption (Intel SGX, AMD SEV), system isolation, clearing memory buffers after use.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>5. Media Sanitization Standards (NIST SP 800-88)</h4>\n<p>Simply deleting a file does not remove it. NIST SP 800-88 Rev 1 defines the three official levels of media sanitization:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Clear:</strong> Overwriting data using logical techniques on user-accessible storage. Protects against basic software recovery tools.</li>\n  <li><strong>Purge:</strong> Applying physical or logical techniques to make target data recovery impossible using advanced laboratory techniques. Includes <em>Degaussing</em> (magnetic media only) and <em>Cryptographic Erase (CE)</em>.</li>\n  <li><strong>Destroy:</strong> Physical destruction of the media (shredding, incineration, pulverizing, acid wash). Data recovery is physically impossible.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"tip-box\" style=\"background: rgba(239,68,68,0.08); border-left: 4px solid #ef4444; padding: 15px; border-radius: 4px; margin-top: 16px;\">\n  <strong>Exam Trap:</strong> Degaussing only works on magnetic media (e.g., HDDs, backup tapes). It does not work on Solid State Drives (SSDs), CDs, or flash drives. For SSDs, cryptographic erase or physical shredding (to 2mm particles) is required.\n</div>\n\n<h4>6. Legal & E-Discovery Frameworks</h4>\n<p>Electronic Discovery (E-Discovery) is the process of identifying, collecting, and producing electronically stored information (ESI) in response to a lawsuit or investigation. The **Electronic Discovery Reference Model (EDRM)** outlines the phases:</p>\n<ol>\n  <li>Information Governance</li>\n  <li>Identification</li>\n  <li>Preservation (Triggering a <strong>Legal Hold</strong> to prevent data deletion/rotation)</li>\n  <li>Collection</li>\n  <li>Processing</li>\n  <li>Review</li>\n  <li>Analysis</li>\n  <li>Production</li>\n  <li>Presentation</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Chain of Custody:</strong> A chronological log tracking who collected, handled, transferred, and stored physical or digital evidence. It preserves the integrity of evidence so it is admissible in court.</p>\n\n<h4>7. Baselines, Scoping & Tailoring</h4>\n<p>Organizations cannot implement every security control. They use standards like NIST SP 800-53 as a starting point:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Scoping:</strong> Removing controls from a baseline that do not apply to the organization's environment (e.g., removing wireless controls if the facility has no Wi-Fi).</li>\n  <li><strong>Tailoring:</strong> Customizing or supplementing controls in the baseline to match the specific risk profile of the organization.</li>\n</ul>\n"};

window.CISSP_DOMAIN_CONTENT[3] = {"title": "Domain 3: Security Architecture and Engineering", "html": "\n<h4>1. Formal Access Control Models</h4>\n<p>State-machine security models define rules mathematically to enforce security policies:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Bell-LaPadula (Confidentiality Focused):</strong> Designed for the US military. Prevents unauthorized disclosure.\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Simple Security Property (No Read Up):</em> A subject at a lower clearance cannot read an object at a higher classification.</li>\n      <li><em>*-Property / Star Property (No Write Down):</em> A subject at a higher clearance cannot write to an object at a lower classification (prevents data leaks).</li>\n      <li><em>Strong Star Property:</em> A subject can only read and write to objects at their exact classification level.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Biba Model (Integrity Focused):</strong> The direct opposite of Bell-LaPadula. Prevents unauthorized modification.\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Simple Integrity Property (No Read Down):</em> A subject cannot read data from a lower integrity level (prevents reading corrupted info).</li>\n      <li><em>*-Integrity Property (No Write Up):</em> A subject cannot write data to a higher integrity level (prevents corrupting clean info).</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Clark-Wilson Model (Commercial Integrity):</strong> Focuses on data integrity within commercial applications. Uses three principles:\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Well-Formed Transactions:</em> Users cannot modify data directly; they must go through software programs that validate changes.</li>\n      <li><em>Separation of Duties:</em> Prevents a single user from carrying out fraud.</li>\n      <li><em>Constrained Data Items (CDIs):</em> Data that must be checked for integrity.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Brewer-Nash (Chinese Wall) Model:</strong> Enforces dynamic conflict of interest boundaries. Prevents consultants or analysts from accessing data of competing companies (e.g., if you work on Pepsi's data, you are blocked from reading Coke's data).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>2. Common Criteria (ISO/IEC 15408)</h4>\n<p>An international standard to evaluate IT security products. Key terminology:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Target of Evaluation (TOE):</strong> The product or system being evaluated.</li>\n  <li><strong>Protection Profile (PP):</strong> A statement of security requirements for a category of products (e.g., \"Firewall requirements\"). Written by the customer or industry.</li>\n  <li><strong>Security Target (ST):</strong> The security claims made by the vendor for their specific product.</li>\n  <li><strong>Evaluation Assurance Levels (EAL):</strong> Rating from EAL 1 (functionally tested) to EAL 7 (formally verified design and tested). EAL 4 is the typical commercial baseline.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>3. Processor Rings & Memory Protections</h4>\n<p>CPUs use hardware segmentation to isolate execution environments:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Ring 0 (Kernel Mode):</strong> Highest privilege. Directly accesses CPU, RAM, and hardware. Operating system kernel resides here.</li>\n  <li><strong>Ring 1 & 2 (OS Services & Drivers):</strong> Intermediate privilege. Used for drivers and OS subsystems.</li>\n  <li><strong>Ring 3 (User Mode):</strong> Lowest privilege. Applications (browsers, word processors) run here. Cannot access hardware directly; must make system calls to Ring 0.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Cryptography: Symmetric vs. Asymmetric</h4>\n<p>Encryption secures data confidentiality. Hashing secures data integrity.</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Symmetric Encryption:</strong> Uses a single shared key for encryption and decryption. Fast and efficient.\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Key Exchange:</em> Difficult to share keys securely.</li>\n      <li><em>Scalability:</em> Scaling requires a unique key for every pair of users. Formula for keys: <span class=\"formula-box\">N(N - 1) / 2</span>. If you have 100 users, you need 100(99)/2 = 4,950 keys.</li>\n      <li><em>Algorithms:</em> AES, 3DES, DES, Blowfish, RC4 (stream cipher), ChaCha20.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Asymmetric Encryption:</strong> Uses a mathematically linked key pair: Public key (shared with everyone) and Private key (kept secret).\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Key Exchange:</em> Simple. Share public key, keep private key.</li>\n      <li><em>Scalability:</em> Scales linearly. Each user needs exactly 2 keys (1 pair). N users need 2N keys.</li>\n      <li><em>Algorithms:</em> RSA, ECC (Elliptic Curve Cryptography - ideal for mobile/IoT due to short key lengths with high security), Diffie-Hellman (used for key agreement, not encryption), El Gamal.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>5. Symmetric Cipher Modes of Operation</h4>\n<p>Block ciphers process data in chunks (blocks). The mode determines how duplicate blocks are handled:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Electronic Codebook (ECB):</strong> The simplest mode. Each block is encrypted independently. Duplicate plaintext blocks result in duplicate ciphertext blocks, revealing patterns (e.g., the Tux penguin image remains visible). <em>Do not use for sensitive data.</em></li>\n  <li><strong>Cipher Block Chaining (CBC):</strong> Each plaintext block is XORed with the preceding ciphertext block before encryption. Uses an <strong>Initialization Vector (IV)</strong> for the first block to ensure randomness.</li>\n  <li><strong>Galois/Counter Mode (GCM):</strong> Provides both confidentiality and integrity/authenticity (AEAD - Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data). Highly efficient, supports parallel processing, widely used in TLS 1.3.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>6. Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) Components</h4>\n<p>PKI manages digital certificates to verify public key ownership:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Certificate Authority (CA):</strong> The trusted third party that signs and issues digital certificates (binds public key to an identity).</li>\n  <li><strong>Registration Authority (RA):</strong> Verifies identity of applicants on behalf of the CA. Does NOT issue certificates.</li>\n  <li><strong>Certificate Revocation List (CRL):</strong> A list of revoked certificates published periodically by the CA. Requires client download.</li>\n  <li><strong>Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP):</strong> A real-time method to check certificate validity. Queries the CA database directly, reducing bandwidth.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>7. TPM & HSM: Hardware Security</h4>\n<p>Hardware devices store secrets securely:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Trusted Platform Module (TPM):</strong> A chip on a computer motherboard. Performs cryptographic functions and stores encryption keys, passwords, and digital certificates. Enables <strong>Secure Boot</strong> by checking boot integrity.</li>\n  <li><strong>Hardware Security Module (HSM):</strong> A physical, network-attached device used to safeguard and manage cryptographic keys for high-performance servers (e.g., CA signing servers, payment processing gateways).</li>\n</ul>\n"};

window.CISSP_DOMAIN_CONTENT[4] = {"title": "Domain 4: Communication and Network Security", "html": "\n<h4>1. The OSI Model & Network PDUs</h4>\n<p>The Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) model standardizes network communications into seven layers. Understanding protocols, hardware, and **Protocol Data Units (PDUs)** at each layer is crucial:</p>\n<table style=\"width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; margin:12px 0;\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr style=\"background:rgba(255,255,255,0.05)\">\n      <th style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); text-align:left; font-size:12px;\">Layer</th>\n      <th style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); text-align:left; font-size:12px;\">PDU Name</th>\n      <th style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); text-align:left; font-size:12px;\">Devices</th>\n      <th style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08); text-align:left; font-size:12px;\">Protocols &amp; Standards</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\"><strong>7. Application</strong></td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Data</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Gateway, WAF</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, SMTP, DNS, SSH, Telnet</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr style=\"background:rgba(255,255,255,0.02)\">\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\"><strong>6. Presentation</strong></td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Data</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">N/A</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">SSL, TLS, JPEG, GIF, ASCII, Compression</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\"><strong>5. Session</strong></td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Data</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">N/A</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">RPC, SQL, NFS, NetBIOS</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr style=\"background:rgba(255,255,255,0.02)\">\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\"><strong>4. Transport</strong></td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Segment (TCP) / Datagram (UDP)</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Load Balancer</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">TCP, UDP, SSL/TLS (layer 4/6 hybrid)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\"><strong>3. Network</strong></td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Packet</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Router, Layer 3 Switch</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">IP (IPv4/IPv6), ICMP, IPsec, ARP (Layer 2/3 hybrid)</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr style=\"background:rgba(255,255,255,0.02)\">\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\"><strong>2. Data Link</strong></td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Frame</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Switch, Bridge, WAP</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Ethernet, Wi-Fi (802.11), PPP, SLIP, Frame Relay</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\"><strong>1. Physical</strong></td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Bits</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Hub, Repeater, Cable</td>\n      <td style=\"padding:8px; border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08);\">Fiber, Cat6, RJ45, RS-232</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n\n<h4>2. TCP 3-Way Handshake & Connections</h4>\n<p>TCP is a connection-oriented, reliable protocol. It establishes connections via a 3-way handshake:</p>\n<ol>\n  <li>Client sends <strong>SYN</strong> (Synchronize) packet containing initial sequence number.</li>\n  <li>Server responds with <strong>SYN-ACK</strong> (Synchronize-Acknowledge) packet.</li>\n  <li>Client responds with <strong>ACK</strong> (Acknowledge) packet.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>SYN Flood Attack:</strong> An attacker sends multiple SYN packets but ignores the server's SYN-ACKs. The server holds half-open connections in its queue, eventually exhausting memory and causing a Denial of Service. <em>Mitigation:</em> SYN Cookies.</p>\n\n<h4>3. Email Security: SPF, DKIM, and DMARC</h4>\n<p>Email (SMTP) has no built-in authentication. Organizations use three DNS-based standards to prevent spoofing and phishing:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>SPF (Sender Policy Framework):</strong> A DNS TXT record listing IP addresses authorized to send emails for a domain. <em>Limitation:</em> Breaks during email forwarding.</li>\n  <li><strong>DKIM (DomainKeys Identified Mail):</strong> Adds a digital signature to the email header. The recipient verifies it using the sender's public key published in DNS. Enforces integrity and non-repudiation.</li>\n  <li><strong>DMARC (Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting, and Conformance):</strong> Ties SPF and DKIM together. Instructs the receiving server what to do if both SPF and DKIM fail (options: <em>none</em>, <em>quarantine</em>, or <em>reject</em>).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Wireless Security Standards</h4>\n<p>Wi-Fi security protocols have evolved significantly due to vulnerabilities:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy):</strong> Unsecure. Uses weak RC4 encryption. Initialization Vectors (IVs) are too short (24-bit), resulting in reuse. Attackers can crack a WEP key in minutes. <em>Do not use.</em></li>\n  <li><strong>WPA2 (802.11i):</strong> Uses robust AES encryption with **CCMP** (Counter Mode Cipher Block Chaining Message Authentication Code Protocol). Secure, but vulnerable to **KRACK** (Key Reinstallation Attack) and offline dictionary attacks on the handshake.</li>\n  <li><strong>WPA3:</strong> Replaces the vulnerable pre-shared key (PSK) handshake with **SAE** (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals). Immune to offline dictionary attacks. Uses forward secrecy.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>5. IPsec VPN Deep Dive</h4>\n<p>IPsec (Internet Protocol Security) is a protocol suite used to encrypt traffic at the Network Layer (Layer 3):</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Authentication Header (AH):</strong> Provides integrity, authentication, and non-repudiation. <strong style=\"color:#ef4444;\">Does NOT provide confidentiality (no encryption).</strong></li>\n  <li><strong>Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP):</strong> Provides confidentiality (encryption), integrity, and authentication.</li>\n  <li><strong>Modes of Operation:</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Transport Mode:</em> Encrypts only the payload. The original IP header is unmodified. Used for host-to-host VPNs.</li>\n      <li><em>Tunnel Mode:</em> Encrypts both the payload and the original IP header. Encapsulates the packet inside a new IP header. Used for site-to-site VPNs.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>6. Firewall Types & Architectures</h4>\n<p>Firewalls block unauthorized traffic based on rules:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Packet Filtering (Static):</strong> Inspects only headers (source/destination IP, ports). Layer 3/4. Fast but easily bypassed. No state tracking.</li>\n  <li><strong>Stateful Inspection:</strong> Keeps track of active connections in a state table. Knows if a packet is part of an established conversation, allowing it through automatically. Highly secure. Layer 3/4.</li>\n  <li><strong>Application Proxy (Gateway):</strong> Acts as a middleman. Completely terminates the connection, inspects the payload at Layer 7, and establishes a new connection to the destination. Highly secure but slow.</li>\n  <li><strong>WAF (Web Application Firewall):</strong> Specifically designed to protect web applications. Inspects Layer 7 HTTP traffic to block SQL injection, Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), and cookie tampering.</li>\n</ul>\n"};

window.CISSP_DOMAIN_CONTENT[5] = {"title": "Domain 5: Identity and Access Management (IAM)", "html": "\n<h4>1. Authentication Factors & MFA</h4>\n<p>Authentication confirms a claimed identity. Multi-factor authentication (MFA) requires presenting **two or more distinct factors**:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Something You Know (Type 1):</strong> Passwords, PINs, security questions, passphrases.</li>\n  <li><strong>Something You Have (Type 2):</strong> Smart cards, hardware tokens, software OTP generators (Google Authenticator), SMS codes.</li>\n  <li><strong>Something You Are (Type 3):</strong> Biometrics (fingerprint, iris, face, voice, retina scan).</li>\n  <li><strong>Somewhere You Are (Type 4 - Contextual):</strong> Geolocation, IP address restriction.</li>\n  <li><strong>Something You Do (Type 5 - Behavioral):</strong> Keystroke dynamics, walking gait, signature speed.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"tip-box\" style=\"background: rgba(239,68,68,0.08); border-left: 4px solid #ef4444; padding: 15px; border-radius: 4px; margin-top: 16px;\">\n  <strong>Exam Trap:</strong> Using a password and a PIN is NOT Multi-Factor Authentication. It is Single-Factor (two of 'Something You Know'). To be MFA, the factors must belong to different categories (e.g., password + SMS token).\n</div>\n\n<h4>2. Biometrics Accuracy Metrics</h4>\n<p>Biometric authentication is measured by error rates and accuracy thresholds:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>False Acceptance Rate (FAR - Type II Error):</strong> The system incorrectly authenticates an unauthorized user (security threat).</li>\n  <li><strong>False Rejection Rate (FRR - Type I Error):</strong> The system incorrectly rejects a legitimate authorized user (user frustration).</li>\n  <li><strong>Crossover Error Rate (CER / EER):</strong> The point where FAR and FRR are equal. The lower the CER, the more accurate the biometric system.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>3. Modern Password Policies (NIST SP 800-63B)</h4>\n<p>NIST guidelines have shifted away from traditional password policies:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Length over Complexity:</strong> Focus on long passphrases (e.g., four random words) instead of complex, hard-to-remember short passwords. Minimum length: 8 characters (14+ recommended for admin).</li>\n  <li><strong>No Forced Periodic Rotation:</strong> Do not force users to change passwords arbitrarily (e.g., every 90 days) unless there is evidence of a compromise. Arbitrary rotation causes users to choose weaker passwords.</li>\n  <li><strong>Screen against Dictionaries:</strong> Block passwords found in lists of known compromised credentials.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Kerberos Authentication Architecture</h4>\n<p>Kerberos is a ticket-based authentication protocol designed for local networks. It relies on a trusted **Key Distribution Center (KDC)** and symmetric encryption:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Authentication Service (AS):</strong> Authenticates the user and issues a **Ticket Granting Ticket (TGT)**.</li>\n  <li><strong>Ticket Granting Service (TGS):</strong> Validates the TGT and issues a **Service Ticket** (ST) for specific resources.</li>\n  <li><strong>Security Risks:</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Golden Ticket Attack:</em> Exploits a compromised Kerberos ticket-granting service account hash (krbtgt) to forge TGTs, granting permanent domain administrator access.</li>\n      <li><em>Silver Ticket Attack:</em> Exploits a compromised service account hash to forge Service Tickets for that specific service, bypassing the KDC.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>5. Access Control Models Compared</h4>\n<p>Different models regulate how subjects (users) access objects (files/systems):</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Discretionary Access Control (DAC):</strong> Access is determined by the resource owner. Flexible but vulnerable (Trojan horses). Windows ACLs are a typical example.</li>\n  <li><strong>Mandatory Access Control (MAC):</strong> Access is determined by the system based on security labels and subject clearance levels. Enforces strict Bell-LaPadula/Biba rules. Used in military environments.</li>\n  <li><strong>Role-Based Access Control (RBAC):</strong> Access is granted based on job functions or roles (e.g., 'Billing Clerk', 'HR Specialist'). Prevents privilege creep. Highly scalable for large organizations.</li>\n  <li><strong>Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC):</strong> Access is determined by evaluating rules based on multiple attributes (Subject, Object, Action, Environment). Highly granular and dynamic (e.g., \"Allow HR to view files if time is between 9 AM - 5 PM and device is corporate\").</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>6. Identity Federation & SSO Protocols</h4>\n<p>Single Sign-On (SSO) allows authenticating once to access multiple independent systems:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>SAML 2.0 (Security Assertion Markup Language):</strong> XML-based framework used for web-based SSO. Coordinates authentication between an <strong>Identity Provider (IdP)</strong> (asserts user identity) and a <strong>Service Provider (SP)</strong> (hosts the app).</li>\n  <li><strong>OAuth 2.0:</strong> An authorization framework, <strong style=\"color:#ef4444;\">NOT an authentication protocol</strong>. Uses tokens (Access/Refresh) to delegate access to APIs on behalf of a user without sharing credentials.</li>\n  <li><strong>OpenID Connect (OIDC):</strong> An authentication layer built on top of OAuth 2.0. Introduces **ID Tokens** (JWT format) to verify user identity. OIDC = OAuth 2.0 (Authorization) + Identity (Authentication).</li>\n</ul>\n"};

window.CISSP_DOMAIN_CONTENT[6] = {"title": "Domain 6: Security Assessment and Testing", "html": "\n<h4>1. Security Assessment, Testing, & Auditing</h4>\n<p>Organizations verify their security posture through three distinct evaluation methods:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Vulnerability Assessment:</strong> A systematic search for security weaknesses (misconfigurations, missing patches) using automated scanners. It identifies and classifies vulnerabilities but <strong style=\"color:#ef4444;\">does NOT exploit them</strong>.</li>\n  <li><strong>Penetration Test:</strong> Goes a step further than an assessment. It involves actively exploiting vulnerabilities to demonstrate real-world impact and bypass controls.</li>\n  <li><strong>Security Audit:</strong> A formal, structured evaluation against a set of compliance standards or policies (e.g., PCI DSS, ISO 27001). Audits are typically performed by an independent third party.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>2. Penetration Testing Methodology (PTES)</h4>\n<p>A structured penetration test follows the **Penetration Testing Execution Standard (PTES)** phases:</p>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Pre-engagement Interactions:</strong> Define scope, rules of engagement, and sign a **Statement of Work (SOW)**.</li>\n  <li><strong>Intelligence Gathering (Reconnaissance):</strong> Passive or active information gathering about the target.</li>\n  <li><strong>Threat Modeling:</strong> Identify target assets and prioritize attack vectors.</li>\n  <li><strong>Vulnerability Analysis:</strong> Find weaknesses in systems.</li>\n  <li><strong>Exploitation:</strong> Bypass security controls and gain access.</li>\n  <li><strong>Post-Exploitation:</strong> Establish persistence, perform privilege escalation, and identify high-value data.</li>\n  <li><strong>Reporting:</strong> Document the findings, risk levels, and remediation steps.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Penetration Test Types:</strong>\n  <ul>\n    <li><em>Black Box:</em> Zero prior knowledge. Simulates external attacker.</li>\n    <li><em>White Box:</em> Full knowledge (source code, credentials, architecture). Simulates insider or developer.</li>\n    <li><em>Gray Box:</em> Partial knowledge (limited credentials or subnet list). Simulates compromised partner or low-level employee.</li>\n  </ul>\n</p>\n\n<h4>3. Vulnerability Scoring (CVSS v3.1)</h4>\n<p>The Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) calculates a score from 0.0 to 10.0 to prioritize risk. The **Base Metric Group** represents the intrinsic characteristics of a vulnerability and contains:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Exploitability Metrics:</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Attack Vector (AV):</em> Physical (P), Local (L), Adjacent (A), Network (N).</li>\n      <li><em>Attack Complexity (AC):</em> Low (L), High (H).</li>\n      <li><em>Privileges Required (PR):</em> None (N), Low (L), High (H).</li>\n      <li><em>User Interaction (UI):</em> None (N), Required (R).</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Impact Metrics:</strong> Confidentiality (C), Integrity (I), Availability (A) \u2014 rated as None, Low, or High.</li>\n  <li><strong>Scope (S):</strong> Unchanged or Changed (whether a vulnerability in one component affects others).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Software Testing Methods: SAST, DAST, and RASP</h4>\n<p>Applications are scanned for code vulnerabilities using different automated tools:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>SAST (Static Application Security Testing):</strong> \"White-box\" testing. Analyzes source code or binaries without executing the program. Finds syntax issues, buffer overflows, and hardcoded secrets early in the SDLC.</li>\n  <li><strong>DAST (Dynamic Application Security Testing):</strong> \"Black-box\" testing. Scans a running application from the outside. Finds vulnerabilities that occur during execution (e.g., session management issues, SQL injection).</li>\n  <li><strong>IAST (Interactive Application Security Testing):</strong> Combines SAST and DAST. Deploys agents inside the running application to monitor code execution and database queries in real time.</li>\n  <li><strong>RASP (Runtime Application Self-Protection):</strong> An agent running inside the application server that detects and blocks attacks in real-time by intercepting system calls.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>5. SOC (Service Organization Control) Reports</h4>\n<p>Organizations verify third-party vendor security through AICPA SOC audits:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>SOC 1:</strong> Audits controls relevant to the user entity's **financial reporting**.</li>\n  <li><strong>SOC 2:</strong> Audits controls relevant to the **Trust Services Criteria** (Security, Availability, Processing Integrity, Confidentiality, Privacy).\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Type I Report:</em> Evaluates control design at a **single point in time**.</li>\n      <li><em>Type II Report:</em> Evaluates control design and **operating effectiveness over a period of time** (typically 6-12 months). <strong style=\"color:#10b981;\">Highly preferred for vendor assessment.</strong></li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>SOC 3:</strong> A high-level, general-use report. Contains no detailed testing descriptions. Can be shared publicly (e.g., on a website).</li>\n</ul>\n"};

window.CISSP_DOMAIN_CONTENT[7] = {"title": "Domain 7: Security Operations", "html": "\n<h4>1. Incident Response Lifecycle (NIST vs. PICERL)</h4>\n<p>Organizations must follow a structured approach to handle security incidents:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>NIST SP 800-61 Lifecycle:</strong>\n    <ol>\n      <li>Preparation</li>\n      <li>Detection &amp; Analysis</li>\n      <li>Containment, Eradication, &amp; Recovery</li>\n      <li>Post-Incident Activity (Lessons Learned)</li>\n    </ol>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>PICERL Model:</strong>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>Preparation:</strong> Training, policy creation, tool setup.</li>\n      <li><strong>Identification:</strong> Detecting indicators of compromise (IOCs).</li>\n      <li><strong>Containment:</strong> Isolating affected hosts to prevent spread (e.g., disconnecting a server from the network).</li>\n      <li><strong>Eradication:</strong> Removing the threat (e.g., deleting malware, patching).</li>\n      <li><strong>Recovery:</strong> Restoring systems to clean production states (e.g., restoring from backups).</li>\n      <li><strong>Lessons Learned:</strong> Post-mortem meeting to improve the process.</li>\n    </ol>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>2. Digital Forensics & Evidence Rules</h4>\n<p>Forensics is the preservation, identification, extraction, and documentation of computer evidence:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Order of Volatility:</strong> Collect evidence starting from the most volatile (easily lost) to the least volatile:\n    <ol>\n      <li>CPU Registers &amp; Cache</li>\n      <li>Routing Table, ARP Cache, Process Table, Kernel Statistics</li>\n      <li>System Memory (RAM)</li>\n      <li>Temporary File Systems / Swap Space</li>\n      <li>Disk Storage (HDDs, SSDs)</li>\n      <li>Remote Logging &amp; Monitoring Data</li>\n      <li>Physical Backups &amp; Archived Media</li>\n    </ol>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Forensic Procedures:</strong> Use a hardware **write blocker** when imaging media. Hash the original disk and the copy to prove they are identical (e.g., MD5/SHA-256).</li>\n  <li><strong>Evidence Rules:</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Best Evidence Rule:</em> Original documents/media should be presented in court rather than copies.</li>\n      <li><em>Hearsay Rule:</em> Secondhand statements are generally inadmissible. However, system logs can be admitted under the **Business Records Exception** if they are generated during normal business operations and not specifically for a trial.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>3. Lockheed Martin Cyber Kill Chain</h4>\n<p>A framework detailing the phases of a targeted cyberattack. Disrupting any phase breaks the attack chain:</p>\n<ol>\n  <li><strong>Reconnaissance:</strong> Gathering information about the target.</li>\n  <li><strong>Weaponization:</strong> Pairing exploits with payloads into a deliverable file (e.g., PDF exploit).</li>\n  <li><strong>Delivery:</strong> Transmitting the weapon to the target (e.g., email attachment).</li>\n  <li><strong>Exploitation:</strong> Triggering the malicious code.</li>\n  <li><strong>Installation:</strong> Establishing a backdoor or trojan on the victim asset.</li>\n  <li><strong>Command &amp; Control (C2):</strong> Establishing a remote channel for control.</li>\n  <li><strong>Actions on Objectives:</strong> Stealing data (exfiltration), altering files, or encrypting systems.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<h4>4. Business Continuity & Disaster Recovery Testing</h4>\n<p>Disaster recovery plans must be tested regularly to verify effectiveness. Tests range in intensity:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Checklist / Walkthrough:</strong> Key team members review the plan document to verify all resources, names, and contact details are up to date. Minimal effort.</li>\n  <li><strong>Tabletop Exercise:</strong> Team members gather in a conference room to talk through a simulated scenario step-by-step. Non-disruptive.</li>\n  <li><strong>Parallel Test:</strong> Systems are restored at the backup recovery site. Production data is mirrored, and systems run in parallel to verify operations, but the primary site remains active and handles actual business traffic.</li>\n  <li><strong>Full Interruption Test:</strong> The primary production site is completely shut down, and operations are migrated to the backup recovery site. High risk, highly disruptive, but provides the most realistic verification.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>5. Backup Strategies & Rotation</h4>\n<p>Data recovery relies on reliable backups:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Full Backup:</strong> Copies all files. Easiest to restore, but takes the longest time and storage.</li>\n  <li><strong>Differential Backup:</strong> Copies all files modified since the last **Full Backup**. Does not clear the archive bit. To restore: requires the last Full backup + the last Differential backup.</li>\n  <li><strong>Incremental Backup:</strong> Copies all files modified since the **Last Backup of any type** (Full or Incremental). Clears the archive bit. To restore: requires the last Full backup + ALL incremental backups since the full backup (restored in order).</li>\n  <li><strong>3-2-1 Rule:</strong> Keep 3 copies of data, on 2 different media types, with 1 copy stored offsite.</li>\n</ul>\n"};

window.CISSP_DOMAIN_CONTENT[8] = {"title": "Domain 8: Software Development Security", "html": "\n<h4>1. Software Development Lifecycle (SDLC) Models</h4>\n<p>SDLC models define the workflow for software creation, each with distinct security considerations:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Waterfall:</strong> A linear, sequential model. Each phase must complete before the next begins. Requirements are locked early. <em>Security issue:</em> Testing happens at the very end, making security fixes extremely expensive.</li>\n  <li><strong>Agile:</strong> Iterative development focusing on small, frequent releases (sprints). Embraces change. <em>Security approach:</em> Integrating security into every sprint (DevSecOps) through automated testing.</li>\n  <li><strong>Spiral:</strong> Risk-driven model. Combines iterative development with systematic risk analysis. Focuses heavily on identifying and mitigating risks at each loop.</li>\n  <li><strong>Software Escrow Agreement:</strong> A legal agreement where a vendor stores source code with a trusted third party. If the vendor goes bankrupt or fails to support the software, the customer is granted access to the source code to maintain it.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>2. DevSecOps & Security Tools</h4>\n<p>DevSecOps integrates security directly into the developer CI/CD (Continuous Integration/Continuous Delivery) pipeline (\"shifting left\"):</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>SAST (Static Application Security Testing):</strong> Code is scanned before compilation (pre-commit or inside the IDE). Finds bugs, buffer overflows, and hardcoded secrets.</li>\n  <li><strong>DAST (Dynamic Application Security Testing):</strong> Scans the running application from the outside, looking for runtime flaws like session management bugs or injection points.</li>\n  <li><strong>SCA (Software Composition Analysis):</strong> Identifies vulnerabilities in third-party libraries and open-source dependencies (e.g., Log4j). Crucial for software supply chain security.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>3. Secure Software Design Principles</h4>\n<p>NIST and Saltzer &amp; Schroeder define foundational principles for secure software design:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>Least Privilege:</strong> Code and users should run with the minimum permissions required to perform their task.</li>\n  <li><strong>Fail-Secure (Fail-Safe):</strong> If a system encounters an error or crashes, it should default to a secure state (e.g., locking access rather than opening it). <em>Contrast: Fail-open allows access (prioritizes availability over security, e.g., a physical fire exit door).</em></li>\n  <li><strong>Defense in Depth (Layered Defense):</strong> Never rely on a single security control. Layer multiple controls (e.g., input validation + firewalls + database restrictions).</li>\n  <li><strong>Complete Mediation:</strong> Every access request to an object must be checked for authorization, without caching credentials or bypasses.</li>\n  <li><strong>Keep Security Simple (Economy of Mechanism):</strong> Keep code and design as simple as possible to make verification easier and reduce bugs.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>4. Injection Vulnerabilities & Defenses</h4>\n<p>Injection occurs when untrusted user input is sent to an interpreter as part of a command or query:</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>SQL Injection (SQLi):</strong> The attacker inputs malicious SQL commands to bypass authentication, read databases, or delete data (e.g., inputting `' OR '1'='1`).\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Defenses:</em> Use **Parameterized Queries (Prepared Statements)** (treats input as data, not executable code), input validation (allowlist), and stored procedures.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Cross-Site Scripting (XSS):</strong> Attacker injects malicious scripts (JavaScript) into a trusted website, which are then executed by a victim's browser.\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Defenses:</em> Context-aware output encoding, input validation, and implementing a strong **Content Security Policy (CSP)** header.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <li><strong>Buffer Overflow:</strong> An application writes more data to a buffer (memory block) than it can hold, overwriting adjacent memory. Can allow executing arbitrary shellcode.\n    <ul>\n      <li><em>Defenses:</em> Use memory-safe languages (Java, Python instead of C/C++), perform bounds checking, and compile with stack protections (ASLR, DEP).</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h4>5. Software Supply Chain & SBOM</h4>\n<p>Attackers target third-party software dependencies to compromise multiple organizations downstream (e.g., SolarWinds hack):</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>SBOM (Software Bill of Materials):</strong> A comprehensive, structured inventory of all third-party libraries, modules, and open-source components used within a software product. Helps quickly identify if an application contains a newly discovered vulnerability (e.g., Log4shell).</li>\n  <li><strong>Dependency Scanning:</strong> Automatically monitors and alerts developers when their code depends on packages with known vulnerabilities or outdated versions.</li>\n</ul>\n"};

